                <aside id="paragraph-10" class="note">
                  <h2 class="icon-wrapper txt-xl">
                      <svg class="icon icon--medium"><use href="/assets/drawable/symbols-v7.svg?#note"></use></svg>
                      <span>You Must Know</span>
                  </h2>
                  <ul><li>Cabbage packs a punch of vitamins and fiber</li><li>The pie reheats beautifully for easy leftovers</li><li>Dill in the sauce adds an extra layer of freshness</li></ul>
                </aside>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                <p>This pie brings back memories of family picnics where everyone gathered around the dish as it was passed hot from the skillet ever since my sister asked for the recipe it has become our standby for weekend lunches</p>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                <h2 id="paragraph-12" class="txt-xxl">Storage Tips</h2>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                <script async src='https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-2184560724232610' crossorigin='anonymous'></script><ins class='adsbygoogle' style='display:block; text-align:center;' data-ad-layout='in-article' data-ad-format='fluid' data-ad-client='ca-pub-2184560724232610' data-ad-slot='6224440029'></ins><script>(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});</script>
                
                
                <p>This cabbage pie will keep in the fridge covered tightly for up to three days It tastes great reheated in a skillet or oven until the edges awaken to crispness again Avoid microwaving if possible as it softens the crust You can freeze slices wrapped well and reheat straight from frozen in a covered pan</p>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                <h2 id="paragraph-14" class="txt-xxl">Ingredient Substitutions</h2>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                <p>No fresh dill Try fresh parsley or chives for a different herbal note Want more protein Add a handful of cooked shredded chicken or crumbled tofu Just ran out of flour Potato starch or a trusted gluten-free blend both work</p>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                <h2 id="paragraph-16" class="txt-xxl">Serving Suggestions</h2>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                <script async src='https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-2184560724232610' crossorigin='anonymous'></script><ins class='adsbygoogle' style='display:block; text-align:center;' data-ad-layout='in-article' data-ad-format='fluid' data-ad-client='ca-pub-2184560724232610' data-ad-slot='5027526978'></ins><script>(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});</script>
                
                
                <p>Serve with a simple tomato salad to balance the richness or add a fried egg for a brunchy twist I love it as a side to soup or as a vegetarian main with roasted new potatoes A light cucumber salad with vinegar makes a refreshing counterpoint</p>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                <h2 id="paragraph-18" class="txt-xxl">Cultural and Historical Context</h2>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                <p>Cabbage pies are beloved across Eastern Europe and Russia with every region putting its own stamp on the dish This version leans toward a skillet pancake approach for speed and convenience It is a modern take on a beloved comfort food especially popular in the cooler months when cabbage shines</p>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
